224
00:14:39,609 --> 00:14:42,929
"Surreal but nice"?
What was I thinking?

225
00:14:48,450 --> 00:14:51,290
[ Doorbell Rings ]

226
00:14:54,130 --> 00:14:56,530
- Hi.
- Hi.

227
00:14:56,610 --> 00:15:00,530
- I forgot my other bag.
- Oh, right. Right.

228
00:15:08,970 --> 00:15:10,850
Thanks.

229
00:15:40,131 --> 00:15:44,732
I'm very sorry about
the "surreal but nice" comment.

230
00:15:44,772 --> 00:15:47,172
- Disaster.
- That's okay.

231
00:15:47,212 --> 00:15:51,772
I thought the apricot and honey thing
was the real low point.

232
00:15:51,852 --> 00:15:53,812
- [ Chuckles ]
- [ Doorknob Rattling ]

233
00:15:53,892 --> 00:15:56,492
Oh, my God.
My flatmate.

234
00:15:56,572 --> 00:15:59,132
I'm sorry.
There's no excuse for him.

235
00:15:59,172 --> 00:16:01,532
[ Clears Throat ]

236
00:16:01,572 --> 00:16:03,452
- Hey.
- Hi.

237
00:16:03,492 --> 00:16:05,772
I'm just going into the kitchen
to get some food.

238
00:16:05,852 --> 00:16:10,013
Then I'm gonna tell you a story
that will make your balls shrink
to the size of raisins.

239
00:16:14,733 --> 00:16:18,173
Probably best
not to tell anyone about this.

240
00:16:18,253 --> 00:16:21,133
Right. Right.
No one.

241
00:16:21,213 --> 00:16:23,413
I mean, I'll tell myself sometimes.

242
00:16:23,493 --> 00:16:26,013
But don't worry.
I won't believe it.

243
00:16:32,173 --> 00:16:34,293
- Bye.
- Bye.

244
00:16:45,254 --> 00:16:48,254
There's something wrong
with this yogurt.

245
00:16:50,054 --> 00:16:53,054
It's not yogurt.
It's mayonnaise.

246
00:16:53,094 --> 00:16:55,054
Oh, right.
There we are then.

247
00:16:55,134 --> 00:16:56,854
Mm.

248
00:16:56,934 --> 00:16:59,694
On for a videofest tonight?

249
00:17:01,054 --> 00:17:04,094
I got some absolute classics.

250
00:17:06,535 --> 00:17:09,455
- Smile.
- No.

251
00:17:12,695 --> 00:17:16,735
- Smile.
- I've got nothing to smile about.

252
00:17:25,415 --> 00:17:27,295
Okay.

253
00:17:27,335 --> 00:17:29,855
In about seven seconds,

254
00:17:29,935 --> 00:17:32,535
I'm going to ask you
to marry me.

255
00:17:38,936 --> 00:17:41,416
[ Spike ]
Imagine.

256
00:17:41,496 --> 00:17:46,096
Somewhere in the world
there's a man who's allowed to kiss her.

257
00:17:46,176 --> 00:17:48,496
[ Both Laughing ]

258
00:17:48,576 --> 00:17:51,176
Yes, she is, uh,

259
00:17:51,256 --> 00:17:54,896
fairly fabulous.

260
00:18:02,696 --> 00:18:05,137
- Do you have any books by Dickens?
- No.

261
00:18:05,217 --> 00:18:09,497
No, I'm afraid we're a travel bookshop.
We only sell travel books.

262
00:18:11,057 --> 00:18:14,177
Oh, right. How about
the new John Grisham thriller?

263
00:18:15,577 --> 00:18:19,417
Well, no, 'cause that's, uh--
that's a novel too, isn't it?

264
00:18:19,497 --> 00:18:22,177
Oh, right.

265
00:18:23,337 --> 00:18:28,377
[ Sighs ]
Have you got Winnie the Pooh?

266
00:18:29,897 --> 00:18:32,258
Martin, your customer.

267
00:18:32,298 --> 00:18:34,298
- Uh, can I help you?
- [ Bell Dinging ]

268
00:18:37,058 --> 00:18:40,618
# [ Pop ]

269
00:18:40,698 --> 00:18:42,978
# Once in a lifetime #

270
00:18:45,258 --> 00:18:47,138
- # [ Continues ]
- Hey.

271
00:18:47,178 --> 00:18:49,058
Hi.

272
00:18:50,538 --> 00:18:55,098
- # Once in a lifetime #
- Just, um, incidentally,

273
00:18:55,178 --> 00:18:58,018
uh, why...
are you wearing that?

274
00:18:58,098 --> 00:19:01,699
Combination of factors really.
Uh, no clean clothes.

275
00:19:01,739 --> 00:19:05,499
There never will be, you know,
unless you actually clean your clothes.

276
00:19:05,579 --> 00:19:07,899
Right.
Vicious circle.

277
00:19:07,979 --> 00:19:10,539
And I was, like,
rooting around in your things...

278
00:19:10,619 --> 00:19:12,539
and I found this,
and I thought "cool".

279
00:19:14,139 --> 00:19:16,619
Kinda... spacey.

280
00:19:19,619 --> 00:19:22,419
There's something wrong
with the goggles, though.

281
00:19:22,459 --> 00:19:25,259
No, they were, um, prescription.

282
00:19:25,339 --> 00:19:28,820
- Groovy.
- So I could see all the fishes properly.

283
00:19:28,860 --> 00:19:31,380
You should do more
of this stuff.

284
00:19:31,460 --> 00:19:35,260
- So, look, any messages today?
- Yeah, I wrote a couple down.

285
00:19:35,340 --> 00:19:38,580
So there were two.
There were two messages? Right?

286
00:19:40,460 --> 00:19:43,660
You want me to write down
all your messages?

287
00:19:43,740 --> 00:19:47,700
Okay, who are the ones
that you didn't write down from?

288
00:19:47,740 --> 00:19:49,460
[ Sighs ]

289
00:19:49,500 --> 00:19:50,900
No. Gone completely.

290
00:19:50,940 --> 00:19:52,820
Oh, no.
There was one from your mum.

291
00:19:52,860 --> 00:19:55,380
She said don't forget lunch,
and her leg's hurting again.

292
00:19:55,460 --> 00:19:57,941
- No one else?
- Absolutely no one else.

293
00:20:01,221 --> 00:20:04,381
Though if we're going for this obsessive
writing down all the message thing,

294
00:20:04,461 --> 00:20:07,741
some American girl called Anna
called a few days ago.

295
00:20:13,061 --> 00:20:15,901
- What did she say?
- Well, it was genuinely bizarre.

296
00:20:15,941 --> 00:20:21,181
She said, "Hi. It's Anna."
Then she said, "Call me at The Ritz"...

297
00:20:21,261 --> 00:20:24,621
and then gave herself
a completely different name.

298
00:20:24,701 --> 00:20:28,462
- Which was?
- Absolutely no idea.

299
00:20:28,542 --> 00:20:30,862
Remembering one name's hard enough.

300
00:20:30,942 --> 00:20:33,102
No, I-- I know that.
She-- She said that.

301
00:20:33,182 --> 00:20:35,342
Um, I know she's using another name.

302
00:20:35,422 --> 00:20:38,702
The problem is
she left the message with my flatmate...

303
00:20:38,782 --> 00:20:40,662
which was a very serious mistake.

304
00:20:40,702 --> 00:20:44,822
Um, I don't know. Imagine, if you will,
the stupidest person you've ever met.

305
00:20:44,902 --> 00:20:48,982
- Are you doing that?
- Yes, sir, I have him in my mind.

306
00:20:49,022 --> 00:20:52,182
And now double it.
And that is the, um-- what can I say--

307
00:20:52,262 --> 00:20:54,743
the git that I am living with.

308
00:20:54,783 --> 00:20:56,143
And he can't remember--

309
00:20:56,223 --> 00:20:59,183
- Try Flintstone.
- I'm sorry, what?

310
00:20:59,263 --> 00:21:02,543
I think she said
her name was Flintstone.

311
00:21:04,543 --> 00:21:09,263
I don't-- I don't suppose, um,
Flintstone rings any bells, does it?

312
00:21:09,343 --> 00:21:12,503
- Oh, I'll put you right through, sir.
- Oh, my God.

313
00:21:15,023 --> 00:21:18,063
Hello. Hi.

314
00:21:18,143 --> 00:21:19,983
- Hi there.
- Hello?

315
00:21:20,063 --> 00:21:21,903
Hi. Hi.

316
00:21:21,983 --> 00:21:25,584
- Sorry. It's William... Thacker.
- Yes?

317
00:21:25,664 --> 00:21:28,064
Um, we-- I work in a bookshop.

318
00:21:28,144 --> 00:21:31,864
Uh-huh. You played it pretty cool there,
waiting for three days to call.

319
00:21:31,904 --> 00:21:35,024
Oh, no, I promise you I've never played
anything cool in my entire life.

320
00:21:35,104 --> 00:21:38,424
My flatmate, who'll I'll stab to death
later, never gave me the message.

321
00:21:39,944 --> 00:21:42,504
I don't know.
Perhaps, um,

322
00:21:42,584 --> 00:21:46,744
I could drop round
for tea later or something.

323
00:21:46,784 --> 00:21:51,585
- Things are pretty busy here.
I might be free around 4:00.
- Right. Right. Great.

324
00:21:51,665 --> 00:21:54,265
- Bye.
- Yea-- Bye.

325
00:21:54,345 --> 00:21:56,825
[ Phone Clicks, Dial Tone ]

326
00:21:59,745 --> 00:22:01,585
Classic.

327
00:22:06,305 --> 00:22:08,145
Classic.

328
00:22:32,746 --> 00:22:35,586
# [ Piano ]

329
00:22:35,626 --> 00:22:38,466
# [ Continues ]

330
00:22:44,546 --> 00:22:47,066
- Which floor?
- Three, please.

331
00:22:52,947 --> 00:22:54,787
[ Elevator Dings ]

332
00:23:14,347 --> 00:23:16,987
Uh, are you sure this is--

333
00:23:17,027 --> 00:23:19,628
Oh, yeah. Yeah. Sure.

334
00:23:30,468 --> 00:23:32,308
- Hi. Hi. I'm Karen.
- Hi.

335
00:23:32,388 --> 00:23:34,788
I'm sorry.
Things are running a little bit late.

336
00:23:34,868 --> 00:23:38,788
Here's the, uh, thing.
Do you wanna come this way?

337
00:23:38,868 --> 00:23:41,468
[ Karen ]
Through here.

338
00:23:41,548 --> 00:23:45,348
[ Reporters Chattering ]

339
00:23:45,388 --> 00:23:47,749
So what did you
think of the film?

340
00:23:47,789 --> 00:23:50,469
Yeah, I thought it was fantastic.
I thought it was, uh,

341
00:23:50,549 --> 00:23:53,949
Close Encounters
meets Jean de Florette.

342
00:23:55,949 --> 00:23:57,829
I agree.

343
00:23:57,869 --> 00:24:00,709
I'm sorry. I didn't get down
what magazines you're from.

344
00:24:00,749 --> 00:24:03,149
- Time Out.
- Great.

345
00:24:03,229 --> 00:24:06,069
And you're from?

346
00:24:08,869 --> 00:24:12,789
Uh, Horse & Hound.

347
00:24:17,030 --> 00:24:20,510
The name's William Thacker. I think,
actually, she might be expecting me.

348
00:24:20,550 --> 00:24:23,230
Oh, okay.
Take a seat and I'll go check.

349
00:24:26,670 --> 00:24:29,950
I see you've, uh--
I see you've brought her some flowers.

350
00:24:29,990 --> 00:24:32,830
[ Laughing ]
No.

351
00:24:32,870 --> 00:24:36,070
These are for my,
um, grandmother.

352
00:24:36,150 --> 00:24:38,790
She's in a hospital
just down the road.

353
00:24:38,870 --> 00:24:41,470
Thought I'd kill two birds
with one stone, you know.

354
00:24:41,550 --> 00:24:44,671
Sure, right.
Absolutely. Yeah. Yeah.

355
00:24:44,751 --> 00:24:47,391
Which hospital's that?

356
00:24:47,431 --> 00:24:49,471
Do you mind me not saying?

357
00:24:49,551 --> 00:24:51,711
It's a rather distressing disease.

358
00:24:51,791 --> 00:24:54,431
- Name of the hospital
kind of gives it away.
- Absolutely. Sure.

359
00:24:54,471 --> 00:24:56,351
Cheers.
Ooh, yes.

360
00:24:56,391 --> 00:24:59,071
Right, uh, Mr. Thacker.
Will you come this way.

361
00:24:59,151 --> 00:25:01,471
Right.

362
00:25:01,511 --> 00:25:04,271
You've got five minutes.

363
00:25:12,712 --> 00:25:15,752
- Hi.
- Hello.

364
00:25:15,832 --> 00:25:19,632
Uh, I brought these, but clearly--

365
00:25:19,712 --> 00:25:23,352
No, they're great.
They're great.

366
00:25:23,432 --> 00:25:26,152
Ah, listen,
I'm sorry about not ringing back.

367
00:25:26,232 --> 00:25:28,072
The whole "two-names concept"...

368
00:25:28,152 --> 00:25:30,552
was totally too much for my flatmate's
pea-sized intellect.

369
00:25:30,632 --> 00:25:34,312
No, it's a stupid privacy thing.
I always pick a... cartoon character.

370
00:25:34,392 --> 00:25:36,512
Last time I was Mrs. Bambi.

371
00:25:36,552 --> 00:25:39,232
[ Door Closes ]

372
00:25:39,272 --> 00:25:42,393
- Everything all right?
- Yes, thank you.

373
00:25:42,473 --> 00:25:45,153
And you're from, uh,
Horse & Hound.

374
00:25:45,193 --> 00:25:47,713
- Yeah.
- Good.

375
00:25:47,753 --> 00:25:50,393
Is that so? Well.

376
00:25:56,113 --> 00:25:58,153
So, uh--

377
00:26:01,153 --> 00:26:06,153
Uh, I'll just... fire away then,
shall I?

378
00:26:07,673 --> 00:26:09,634
Right.

379
00:26:09,714 --> 00:26:11,594
Uh--

380
00:26:12,954 --> 00:26:16,154
The film's great, and, um,

381
00:26:16,234 --> 00:26:19,074
I just was wondering whether...

382
00:26:19,154 --> 00:26:21,234
you ever thought of having, um,

383
00:26:21,314 --> 00:26:24,874
more, uh, horses in it.

384
00:26:24,954 --> 00:26:27,834
[ Clears Throat ]

385
00:26:27,914 --> 00:26:31,274
Uh, well, we would have liked to,

386
00:26:31,354 --> 00:26:36,474
but it was, um, difficult,
obviously, being set in space.

387
00:26:37,915 --> 00:26:41,595
Space, right, yeah.
Yeah, obviously very difficult.

388
00:26:42,955 --> 00:26:44,795
I'm so sorry.
I arrived outside.

389
00:26:44,875 --> 00:26:46,755
They thrust this thing
into my hand--

390
00:26:46,795 --> 00:26:49,955
No, it's my fault.
I thought this would all be over by now.

391
00:26:50,035 --> 00:26:52,675
I just wanted to sort of apologize
for the kissing thing.

392
00:26:52,715 --> 00:26:54,595
I seriously don't know
what came over me.

393
00:26:54,635 --> 00:26:57,515
And I just wanted to make sure
that you were fine about it.

394
00:26:59,275 --> 00:27:04,515
- Yeah, yeah, yeah. Absolutely fine.
- [ Door Closes ]

395
00:27:04,595 --> 00:27:08,596
Do remember that Miss Scott is also
keen to talk about her next project...

396
00:27:08,676 --> 00:27:12,196
which is, um, shooting
later in the summer.

397
00:27:12,276 --> 00:27:15,596
Ah, yes, excellent.
Excellent.

398
00:27:20,396 --> 00:27:24,356
Any horses in that one?

399
00:27:24,396 --> 00:27:29,636
Or hounds for that matter. Our readers
are equally intrigued by both species.

400
00:27:29,676 --> 00:27:32,356
It takes place on a submarine.

401
00:27:32,436 --> 00:27:35,757
Oh. Well, bad luck.

402
00:27:37,117 --> 00:27:39,637
But, um,

403
00:27:39,717 --> 00:27:41,917
if there were horses in it,

404
00:27:41,997 --> 00:27:44,477
would you be riding them...

405
00:27:44,557 --> 00:27:48,997
or would you be getting, a--
a stunt-horse-double-man-thing?

406
00:27:51,277 --> 00:27:55,917
[ Chuckles ] I-- I'm a complete moron.
I apologize. I--

407
00:27:55,997 --> 00:27:59,757
This is very weird. It's the sort
of thing that happens in dreams,

408
00:27:59,797 --> 00:28:02,277
not in real life.

409
00:28:02,357 --> 00:28:04,758
I mean, good dreams.
It's a--

410
00:28:04,838 --> 00:28:08,238
it's a dream, in fact,
uh, to see you again.

411
00:28:09,758 --> 00:28:13,278
What happens next in the dream?

412
00:28:15,078 --> 00:28:19,278
I suppose in the, uh, dream--

413
00:28:19,318 --> 00:28:22,758
dream scenario--
I just, uh,

414
00:28:22,798 --> 00:28:24,918
change my personality...

415
00:28:24,998 --> 00:28:27,518
because you can do that
in dreams and, um,

416
00:28:29,798 --> 00:28:33,879
walk over and, uh, kiss the girl.

417
00:28:33,959 --> 00:28:36,479
But, uh--

418
00:28:43,839 --> 00:28:47,399
Time's up, I'm afraid.
Did you get what you wanted?

419
00:28:47,479 --> 00:28:52,479
- Um, nearly, nearly.
- Well, maybe just one last question.

420
00:28:53,799 --> 00:28:56,319
- Sure. [ Clears Throat ]
- Right, right.

421
00:28:57,919 --> 00:28:59,760
[ Door Closes ]

422
00:28:59,840 --> 00:29:03,080
Are you... busy tonight?

423
00:29:03,160 --> 00:29:07,840
- Yes.
- Right. Right.

424
00:29:09,360 --> 00:29:13,160
- Come in.
- Well, it was nice to meet you.

425
00:29:13,240 --> 00:29:15,400
Yes, and you.

426
00:29:15,480 --> 00:29:17,800
Surreal... but nice.

427
00:29:17,880 --> 00:29:22,080
Thank you. You are Horse & Hounds'
favorite actress.

428
00:29:23,400 --> 00:29:25,760
You and Black Beauty...

429
00:29:25,840 --> 00:29:27,680
tied.

430
00:29:32,601 --> 00:29:34,441
How was she?

431
00:29:34,521 --> 00:29:37,881
Oh, um, fabulous.

432
00:29:37,921 --> 00:29:41,881
Excellent. Wait a minute.
She took your grandmother's flowers.

433
00:29:41,921 --> 00:29:45,361
Uh, yeah, yeah.
That's right.

434
00:29:45,441 --> 00:29:47,401
- Bitch.
- [ Karen ] Oh, Mr. Thacker.

435
00:29:47,481 --> 00:29:51,721
Mr. Thacker, if you'd like to come with
me, we can rush you through the others.

436
00:29:51,801 --> 00:29:53,161
The others?

437
00:29:53,241 --> 00:29:55,721
Mr. Thacker is from Horse & Hound.

438
00:29:58,562 --> 00:30:01,162
- How's it going?
- Very well, thank you.

439
00:30:01,242 --> 00:30:04,322
Have a seat.

440
00:30:04,362 --> 00:30:07,442
- Well, did you enjoy the film?
- [ Clock Ticking ]

441
00:30:07,522 --> 00:30:10,442
Yes, enormously.

442
00:30:10,522 --> 00:30:12,282
- Well, fire away.
- Right.

443
00:30:13,762 --> 00:30:16,002
Did you enjoy making the film?

444
00:30:16,082 --> 00:30:19,842
- Yes, I did.
- Good.

445
00:30:19,882 --> 00:30:22,242
Any bit in particular?

446
00:30:22,322 --> 00:30:25,322
You tell me what bit
you enjoyed the most,

447
00:30:25,402 --> 00:30:28,283
and I'll tell you
if I enjoyed making that bit.

448
00:30:30,243 --> 00:30:33,803
Uh, l...

449
00:30:33,883 --> 00:30:36,763
liked the bit in space...

450
00:30:36,843 --> 00:30:38,723
very much.

451
00:30:38,763 --> 00:30:42,203
Did you identify with the character
you're playing?

452
00:30:42,243 --> 00:30:45,723
[ Speaking Spanish ]

453
00:30:45,763 --> 00:30:49,723
- No.
- No.

454
00:30:51,523 --> 00:30:55,164
Oh. Why not?

455
00:30:56,000 --> 00:30:57,564
[ Spanish ]

456
00:30:58,100 --> 00:31:01,284
[ Spanish ]

457
00:31:01,324 --> 00:31:04,844
Because he's playing
a psychopathic flesh-eating robot.

458
00:31:04,924 --> 00:31:07,044
Classic.

459
00:31:07,124 --> 00:31:09,804
So, uh,

460
00:31:09,884 --> 00:31:12,364
is this your first film?

461
00:31:12,444 --> 00:31:15,204
No. It's my 22nd.

462
00:31:15,244 --> 00:31:19,044
Of course it is.
Any favorites among the 22?

463
00:31:20,404 --> 00:31:22,244
Working with Leonardo.

464
00:31:22,324 --> 00:31:26,205
- Da Vinci?
- DiCaprio.

465
00:31:26,285 --> 00:31:29,045
Of course.
[ Chuckles ]

466
00:31:29,125 --> 00:31:32,925
And is-- is he your favorite
Italian director?

467
00:31:33,045 --> 00:31:35,365
[ Reporters Chattering ]

468
00:31:37,285 --> 00:31:40,285
- Mr. Thacker.
- Oh, no.

469
00:31:40,365 --> 00:31:43,045
- Have you got a minute?
- No.

470
00:31:48,765 --> 00:31:50,245
Hi.

471
00:31:52,326 --> 00:31:54,206
Hi.

472
00:31:54,246 --> 00:31:57,806
Um-- Yeah, so the, um--

473
00:31:57,886 --> 00:32:01,966
the-- the thing I was doing tonight,
I'm not doing anymore.

474
00:32:02,046 --> 00:32:04,446
I told them I had
to spend the evening...

475
00:32:04,486 --> 00:32:08,166
with Britain's premier
equestrian journalist.

476
00:32:08,206 --> 00:32:11,166
Oh. Well, great.

477
00:32:11,246 --> 00:32:13,366
Fantastic.
That's, uh--

478
00:32:13,446 --> 00:32:16,526
Oh. Shittity brickitty.

479
00:32:16,606 --> 00:32:20,007
It's my sister's birthday. Shit.
We're meant to be having dinner.

480
00:32:20,087 --> 00:32:22,887
- Okay, that's fine.
- No. I'm sure I can get out of it.

481
00:32:22,927 --> 00:32:26,247
No, I mean, if it's fine with you,
I'll be your date.

482
00:32:27,767 --> 00:32:30,727
You--
You'll be my date...

483
00:32:30,807 --> 00:32:33,447
to my little sister's
birthday party?

484
00:32:33,487 --> 00:32:37,127
- If it's all right.
- Well, yeah, I'm sure it's all right.

485
00:32:37,167 --> 00:32:38,967
My friend Max is cooking,

486
00:32:39,047 --> 00:32:41,887
and he is generally acknowledged
